# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js App Router project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed Dependencies
- Added `@vercel/analytics` (v1.6.1) to project dependencies
- Updated `package.json` to include the new dependency
- Updated `package-lock.json` with the new package and its dependencies (97 packages added)

### 2. Modified Files
**frontend/app/layout.tsx**
- Imported `Analytics` component from `@vercel/analytics/next`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the main application content
- Placement ensures analytics tracking works correctly without interfering with the existing layout structure

## Implementation Details
- **Project Type**: Next.js App Router (using `app` directory)
- **Package Manager**: npm
- **Root Layout**: `frontend/app/layout.tsx`
- **Analytics Component Placement**: Inside `<body>` tag, after `<AppProvider>` wrapper

## Testing & Verification
✅ **Build Test**: Successfully built the project with `npm run build` - no errors
✅ **TypeScript Compilation**: Passed TypeScript checks during build
✅ **Static Generation**: All 9 routes compiled successfully
✅ **Dependencies**: All packages installed without vulnerabilities

## Notes
- The Analytics component was placed after the main application content to ensure it doesn't interfere with the existing UI structure
- The implementation follows Vercel's recommended approach for Next.js App Router projects
- Analytics will automatically track page views and Web Vitals once deployed to Vercel
- No additional configuration is required - the component works out of the box
